We will explore a dataset of Melbourne house price data (available via Kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/anthonypino/melbourne-housing-market) with a view to modellijng the relationship between variables using a Linear Regression model.

I have removed several fields from the dataset to make the analysis slightly simpler, and more generalisable.

In [1]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

sns.set()
%matplotlib inline
plt.rcParams['figure.dpi'] = 300
plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (8,5)

With the usual libraries imported and plot parameters set, we can load the dataset.

We then drop all rows containing any NA values. This is to make our demonstration easier and cleaner. This will of course reduce the size of the dataset and may bias it (if the missing values disproportionately represented, for example, cheaper properties) so in a 'real' analysis this is not a decision to be taken lightly.

In [2]:
housing = pd.read_csv("Melbourne_housing_FULL.csv")
housing.dropna(inplace=True)

Let's have a look at some basic info about the data, including showing which columns I've kept from the original dataset.

And now for that staple of exploratory data analysis, the scatterplot matrix (or pair plot, correlogram and probably other names too).

In [5]:
sns.pairplot(housing)
plt.show()

I'd say the strongest correlation visible there is rooms:bedrooms. Hardly a surprise. But that's no bad thing: it indicates a well distributed dataset and the absence of any one dominant variable - all the better for demonstrating a linear regression.

The corr() function tells us much the same thing without the visualisation, if that's more your thing:

Price is going to be our dependent variable, so let's have a look how it's distributed in the source data:

In [7]:
sns.distplot(housing.Price)
plt.show()

The long right tail suggests to me that a logarithmic visualisation might be more appropriate:

In [8]:
sns.distplot(np.log10(housing.Price))
plt.show()

That;s much closer to a normal distribution. Note the secondary peak around 6.1. This could be a statistical fluke due to insufficient data, or could indicate something psychological; once the approximate value of a house reaches a particular point (1 million dollars in this case), prices are more likely to tend towards 'round' figures. I'm sure a behavioural economist would have more to say about this.

Moving towards prediction, we set up our independent ($X$) variables, and our dependent ($y$)

In [9]:
X = housing[["Rooms", "Distance", "Bedroom2", "Bathroom", "Car", "Landsize", "BuildingArea", "YearBuilt"]]
y = housing["Price"]

And use sklearn to split our data into a training set (70%) and test (30%):

(Random state is set for reproducibility on this notebook, but would be left out in a 'real' situation.)

In [10]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=23)

And train the model:

In [11]:
lm = LinearRegression()
lm.fit(X_train, y_train)
Out[11]:
LinearRegression(copy_X=True, fit_intercept=True, n_jobs=None,
         normalize=False)

And use it to predict on the test data:

In [12]:
predictions = lm.predict(X_test)

Finally we will visualise our prediction accuracy:

In [13]:
sns.regplot(x=np.log10(y_test), y=np.log10(predictions), scatter_kws={"color":"black","alpha":0.5,"s":2}, fit_reg=True)
plt.ylim(5,7)
plt.xlim(5,7)
plt.title("Predicted vs Actual House Prices")
plt.xlabel("Actual (log10)")
plt.ylabel("Predicted (log10)")
plt.show()

I used log10 scales again to ensure a reasonably distributed chart. On a normal scale there would be a dense cluster of points in the bottom left and little elsewhere.

We can see our simple linear regression is reasonably accurate. It appears to overvalue less valuable properties and undervalue more valuable ones (suggesting too great an intercept and too small a gradient) but it doesn't perform badly overall.
